{
  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Anticipatory Sensor Fusion with Temporal Credibility Forecasting' (ASFT-CF) for robust UAV navigation under dynamic environmental conditions. The core idea is to move beyond conventional late or early fusion techniques by introducing a meta-cognitive layer that forecasts the temporal credibility of individual sensory modalities—particularly sequential visual features (from monocular or stereo cameras) and positional features (from IMU, barometer, or VIO pipelines)—over a predictive horizon. Instead of assuming equal reliability across time, ASFT-CF employs a dual-path architecture: (1) a spatiotemporal feature encoder that processes sequences of visual and inertial inputs using transformer-based memory networks to capture long-range dependencies; and (2) a credibility forecasting module that uses these encoded representations to predict per-modality confidence scores one or more steps ahead. These forecasts are then fed into an adaptive fusion controller—a differentiable gating network—that dynamically reweights the contribution of each modality in pose estimation and trajectory planning. Crucially, the credibility model is trained using self-supervised discrepancy signals (e.g., photometric error, inertial integration drift, optical flow inconsistency) and environmental context (e.g., texture richness, motion speed, lighting gradients), enabling it to learn patterns such as 'high angular velocity leads to visual blur within 0.5 seconds' or 'low-texture corridors induce VIO failure after 3 seconds'. To enhance trustworthiness, we integrate a selective execution protocol inspired by selective classification: if all modalities are forecasted to be below a confidence threshold, the system triggers safe fallback behaviors instead of making erroneous decisions. This anticipatory design significantly improves resilience in GNSS-denied scenarios where traditional systems fail due to delayed reaction to sensor degradation. The framework will be evaluated on both simulated environments (using AirSim with perturbed weather, dynamic obstacles, and signal dropouts) and real-world datasets collected under challenging conditions. We expect this approach to reduce navigation drift by at least 40% compared to state-of-the-art VIO and visual-inertial fusion baselines, while increasing mission completion rates in turbulent or visually degraded settings. Potential broader impacts include safer autonomous delivery drones, reliable search-and-rescue UAVs, and foundational advances in trustworthy AI for embodied agents.",
