{
  "Idea": "We propose a novel cognitive architecture titled 'Physics-Informed Anticipatory Fusion with Observability Forecasting' (PIAFF) for robust UAV navigation under dynamic environmental conditions. The core contribution lies in embedding a learned model of intuitive physics within the sensor fusion pipeline to forecast not only sensor credibility but also environmental observability—the degree to which the surrounding scene will support accurate perception in the near future. Unlike conventional fusion methods that react to signal degradation after it occurs, PIAFF leverages a dual-loop design: (1) an inner adaptive fusion loop processes sequential visual and inertial data through spatiotemporal transformers, dynamically reweighting modalities via a differentiable gating network; and (2) an outer anticipatory loop employs a multimodal generative world model trained to simulate short-term physical evolutions of the environment—such as lighting transitions, object motion, wind-induced vibrations, and occlusion patterns—from current sensory inputs. This world model generates synthetic future observations and predicts their perceptual quality (e.g., texture contrast, optical flow coherence, IMU noise amplification), which are then used to compute forward-looking observability scores. These scores inform a physics-grounded credibility forecaster that adjusts fusion weights proactively. Crucially, the generative model is trained using self-supervised objectives derived from photometric consistency, inertial plausibility, and event-based sharpness detection, allowing it to learn mappings between motion plans and expected sensory outcomes. For example, if the model predicts that entering a tunnel will cause a sudden luminance drop exceeding camera dynamic range, it preemptively increases reliance on inertial priors and triggers exposure compensation. To ensure safety, the system integrates a hierarchical selective execution protocol: at the trajectory level, it avoids